# Getting Started

## Install and launching R packages

The code chunk below uses p_load() of pacman package to check if tidyverse packages are installed in the computer. If they are, then they will be launched into R.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
pacman::p_load(tidyverse)
```
:::


## Importing the data


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
library(readr)
exam_data <- read_csv("data/Exam_data.csv")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}
```
Rows: 322 Columns: 7
── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Delimiter: ","
chr (4): ID, CLASS, GENDER, RACE
dbl (3): ENGLISH, MATHS, SCIENCE

ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
```
:::
:::


# Plotting a simple bar chart

## Bar chart


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,
       aes(x=RACE))+
  geom_bar()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-3-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


### Horizontal bar chart

Use coordinate to change bar into horizontal


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,
       aes(x=RACE))+
  geom_bar()+
  coord_flip()+
  theme_minimal()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-4-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


## Histogram


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
hist(exam_data$MATHS)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-5-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


default setting of bins are 30


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=MATHS))+
  geom_histogram(bins=10, 
                color='red',
                 fill='blue')+
  ggtitle("Histogram")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-6-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=MATHS,fill=GENDER))+
  geom_histogram(bins=20, color="grey30")#color in histogram is bin line color
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-7-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


## Density plot

it is a good way to replace histogram for continuous data if its distribution is smooth


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=MATHS,colour=GENDER))+
  geom_density() 
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-8-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


## Dotplot


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=MATHS))+
  geom_dotplot(dotsize=0.5,binwidth = 3)+
  scale_y_continuous(NULL,breaks = NULL) #remove y-axis value
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


## Boxplot and Notch

Notch(缺口) can check by whether notches are overlapping to see whether medians are the same


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=GENDER,y=MATHS))+
  geom_boxplot(notch=TRUE)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


## Violin Plot

Can compare more clearly about the difference of distributions of multiple data


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=GENDER,y=MATHS))+
  geom_violin()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-11-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


## Scatter plot


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=ENGLISH,y=MATHS))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()+
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0,100),ylim=c(0,100))
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}
```
`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'
```
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-12-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


### Combine scatter and boxplot


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=GENDER,y=MATHS))+
  geom_point(position="jitter",size=0.2)+
  geom_boxplot()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-13-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


### Statistical summary

Add statistical summary can use stat_summary or overwrite by a new geom\_ setting


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=GENDER,y=MATHS))+
  geom_point(position='jitter')+
  geom_boxplot()+
  stat_summary(geom="point",fun='mean',color='red',size=4)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-14-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=GENDER,y=MATHS))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_point(stat="summary",        
             colour ="red",          
             size=4)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}
```
No summary function supplied, defaulting to `mean_se()`
```
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-15-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


## Create 2D panel


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=MATHS))+
  geom_histogram(bins=20)+
  facet_wrap(~CLASS)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-16-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


### Two discrete variables can use facet_grid


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data=exam_data,aes(x=MATHS))+
  geom_histogram(bins=20)+
  facet_grid(~CLASS)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](Hands-on_Ex01_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-17-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::
